AGI - If the Iranian President, Ebrahim Raisi>, died in the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-19/ helicopter-president-iraniano-raisi-26446918/"> incident</a> which involved his helicopter, his role would be assumed immediately by the first executive vice-president, Moberham This is what Article 131 of the Constitution of the Islamic Republic provides for. The appointment should however be confirmed by the Supreme Guide, the ayatollah Ali Khamenei>, which has the last word on all matters of state.
&nbsp;
A provisional authority established, a council composed of the first Vice-President, the President of the Chamber, Mohammad Bagher Ghalibaf>, and the head of the judiciary, Gholam-Hossein Mohseni-Ejei>, will have the task of organizing the election of a new president within the maximum term of 50 days. Khamenei can, however, alternatively decide to ask the council to appoint a successor without resorting to urns to avoid a transition phase in a complex period such as the current one, marked by the war between Israel and Hamas.
&nbsp;
In the case of an investigation dropped from above, most analysts point to Ghalibaf, former mayor of Tehran and former general of the Guardians of the Revolution, a figure surviving all the Khamenei purges and who long aspires to the presidency. Both Mokhber and Mohseni-Ejei are considered as loyal executioners of the Supreme Guide orders that, if Ghalibaf was chosen, they should not be traversed for personal ambitions. Even the current head of the judiciary, figure that is personally appointed by Khamenei without Parliament's validation, could have some chance.
&nbsp;
Raisi was elected president in 2021. The next elections are currently scheduled in 2025.&nbsp;

